Title of Services Post','Morbi leo nisi, tempus vel diam ut, consequat mattis dui. ','inherit','open','open','','1379-revision','','','2014-02-05 17:07:20','2014-02-05 17:07:20','',1379,'http://172.16.100.211/wordpress/?p=1380',0,'revision','',0),(1381,1,'2014-02-04 21:19:49','2014-02-04 21:19:49','<strong>Prototyping</strong> – developing software projects or visual mock-ups to test out a specific concept by allowing stakeholders to interact directly. Prototyping allows programs to better gather and refine requirements and test software and architectural approaches without the heavy commitment of resources. Historically, the Lab has created mobile apps for smartphones and tablets, HTML5 web applications, web site wireframes and slideshow decks.\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Virtual Project Space</strong> – temporary, virtualized environments isolated from the CDC network with servers and desktop virtual machines (e.g., Windows XP, Windows Server, RedHat Linux, CentOS Linux, etc.) (link to http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_machine) within the Lab’s private cloud, but available remotely by PC, Mac, iPad or other devices using an encrypted connection. The Lab provides cloud computational, disk and memory resources in the form of customizable and configurable virtual machines that programs have administrative control over to install and test software and network configurations. Although engagement environments are virtual, the user experience is identical to the resources provided by traditional hardware based server and desktop computers. Programs have used our virtual project space to perform alternatives analysis, user acceptance testing, baseline configuration development and estimating what Hardware/software resources are required for procurement.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Evaluation</strong> – structured evaluations of technology, practices or tools to assess their potential impact for public health. Lab personnel review existing or planned informatics or IT tools to help programs integrate (if appropriate) new approaches.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Physical Collaboration Space</strong> – the Lab has a physical location with demonstration capabilities, large video display, SmartBoard technology, Windows and Mac OSX workstations in an enclaved local area network that allows programs to meet in person for brainstorming, social media campaigns, communication activities, training, focus groups, and software demonstrations.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Open Source Development Tools</strong> – The Lab hosts a set of software development collaboration tools at code.phiresearchlab.org. CODE has a source code repository (currently Subversion with additional repository types soon to come), issue tracking &amp; project management (JIRA) and blog/wiki/content management (Confluence) available for use by public health projects that need to collaborate with diverse partners. Projects can administer their own project spaces within these tools to best meet the needs of their development projects (e.g., add/change user permissions, design blog/wiki layout and content, share source and runtime files).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Consultation</strong> – The Lab’s cross-functional team is available for conversations to discuss and plan approaches to and strategies for particular informatics and technology questions. Programs have used the Lab to review environmental scanning and market research, investigate different architectural approaches and plan use of lab resources for prototyping and/or virtual project space.</p>','Services','','inherit','open','open','','1198-revision-5','','','2014-02-04 21:19:49','2014-02-04 21:19:49','',1198,'http://172.16.100.211/wordpress/?p=1381',0,'revision','',0),(1383,1,'2014-02-05 17:10:23','2014-02-05 17:10:23','<strong>Prototyping</strong> – developing software projects or visual mock-ups to test out a specific concept by allowing stakeholders to intera